        introduction: "The taxi from Annemasse to Chamonix-Mont-Blanc is one of Haute-Savoie's most spectacular journeys, connecting the French-Swiss border town to the world capital of mountaineering in just over an hour. Annemasse, a dynamic urban hub at the gateway to Geneva where over 90,000 cross-border workers commute daily, sits beneath the limestone cliffs of the Saleve. The journey via the A40 Autoroute Blanche is a progressive ascent into high mountain country through increasingly alpine landscapes. After the Genevois hills, the Arve valley narrows between the Faucigny massifs, gradually revealing the snow-capped Chamonix Aiguilles. Beyond Sallanches, where the Mont-Blanc massif appears in full glory on clear days, the road enters the narrowing gorges leading to Chamonix. Chamonix-Mont-Blanc (1,035 m) sits at the foot of Western Europe's highest peak (4,808 m), birthplace of mountaineering since Balmat and Paccard's 1786 first ascent and host of the first Winter Olympics in 1924. The Aiguille du Midi cable car (3,842 m), the Mer de Glace glacier and the UTMB ultra-trail make this one of the world's greatest mountain destinations. This transfer is especially popular with skiers and mountaineers arriving via Geneva airport.",
        itineraire: "Your driver leaves Annemasse south-east via the A40 Autoroute Blanche serving the entire Arve valley. The motorway first crosses the Genevois plain with the imposing Saleve on the left and the Mole (1,863 m) ahead. After Bonneville, the road enters the narrowing Faucigny valley. Cluses, mid-journey, is the valley's gateway framed by the Bargy cliffs. Beyond Cluses, the landscape becomes distinctly alpine: fir forests, rushing torrents, hamlets clinging to slopes. At Sallanches, the Mont-Blanc massif reveals itself in full splendour. The RN205 takes over after Le Fayet-Saint-Gervais, climbing through the Arve gorges past Servoz and Les Houches to Chamonix. Tolls about €7 (included). Allow 1h05 normally, 1h20-1h25 at peak hours and on Saturday tourist changeover days.",
        conseils: "If arriving from Geneva via Annemasse, plan for traffic: on Saturday changeover days (early December, late February, Easter, mid-July) the Arve valley is often saturated. Leave before 7am or after 2pm. In winter, the Sallanches-Chamonix road can be snowy or icy — our vehicles always carry winter tyres and drivers are experienced in alpine conditions. In Chamonix, don't miss the Aiguille du Midi cable car (€65 return, advance online booking strongly recommended in high season): the 3,842 m panorama is unique, featuring the Step into the Void glass pod suspended above a 1,000 m drop. The Mer de Glace is reached by the Montenvers railway (€35 return, allow 2h including the ice cave). For ski and mountain gear, specify your needs when booking for a suitable vehicle (estate car or 7-seat van).",
        comparaisonTransport: "The SNCF train Annemasse — Chamonix via Saint-Gervais takes about 2h for €15-20, with beautiful scenery but double the travel time. The Lihsa bus takes 1h30-2h. The TaxiNeo taxi at €100 — €135 is direct door-to-door in 1h05 with luggage and ski gear handled. For 3-4 passengers (€25-45/person), reasonable per-person pricing for considerable comfort and time savings.",
